article.headline: Michigan State 71, Michigan 54
article.story: EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Paul Davis had 22 points and seven rebounds to lead Michigan State to a 71-54 victory over Michigan on Saturday. The Spartans (7-7, 2-1 Big Ten) beat their rival for the ninth time in 10 meetings. Daniel Horton scored 20 points on 5-of-15 shooting for the Wolverines (10-4, 1-2) and didn't get much help from his teammates, especially Bernard Robinson. Robinson, who was averaging a team-high 14.2 points, made just 2 of 8 shots and had five points. He made a 3-pointer -- off the glass -- early in the first half, and did not score again until there was two minutes left. The Spartans outscored Michigan 12-2 to close the first half and take a 32-23 lead, which they had no trouble maintaining after halftime. The Wolverines made the first basket of the second half, but couldn't get closer the rest of the way and had few single-digit deficits. Both teams had only one scorer in double digits, but the Spartans had seven players score at least six. Maurice Ager had nine points and eight rebounds, Alan Anderson scored nine, and Jason Andreas scored a season-high seven points. Davis was 6-of-12 from the field and 9-of-11 at the free throw line, and fell two points short of the career high he set in a loss to Kentucky this season. Lester Abram scored nine for the Wolverines, who had 22 turnovers and just eight assists. Both teams started the game shooting well. Michigan State made its first four 3-pointers, and Michigan connected on its first three 3-pointers. The Wolverines took a 19-15 lead with 10:10 left in the first half -- then they went cold. They made only one field goal and scored just four points before halftime in what was the decisive stretch of the game. <
